<Layout title="Easements on Property in Brisbane: What Sellers and Buyers Need to Know 2026 | Daniel Gierach Property" description="A practical guide to easements on Brisbane properties in 2026, covering types of easements, disclosure obligations, how buyers react, and what sellers need to do before listing.">

<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is an easement on a property in Queensland?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "An easement is a registered right that allows a person or entity other than the property owner to use part of the land for a specific purpose. Common examples in Brisbane include drainage easements, access easements that allow a neighbour to cross your land to reach theirs, and easements in favour of utility providers such as Energex or Unity Water. Easements run with the land and are binding on current and future owners."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do I have to disclose easements when selling a property in Queensland?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. Easements registered on the title must be disclosed as part of the contract of sale. In Queensland, a registered easement appears on the title search that your conveyancer obtains as part of the contract preparation. The contract typically includes the title reference, and the buyer or their solicitor will obtain the full title search before proceeding to an unconditional contract. You should also disclose any unregistered easements or informal access arrangements you are aware of."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do easements affect the sale price of a property in Brisbane?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Whether an easement affects value depends on its type and location. A drainage easement running along the rear boundary of a standard residential lot in Brisbane's inner east typically has little practical impact and does not materially affect buyer demand or sale price. An access easement that limits where the owner can build, or an easement that runs through the main usable area of the yard, can affect value more significantly. Buyers in Brisbane's inner east are generally familiar with easements and respond to them proportionally based on their practical impact."
      }
    }
  ]
}
</script>

<article style="background:var(--color-surface-0);min-height:100vh;">

